{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:08:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1605"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1605"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.17,0.06,0.02,0.71]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67658"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28207"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of severe pain on swallowing. He has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease for ten years, hypertension, and chronic lower back pain. His medications include a proton pump inhibitor, ramipril, and pregabalin. He has been taking tetracycline for the past three weeks for treatment of severe acne. He does not smoke and has no other medical conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An urgent endoscopy reveals white plaques with surrounding normal mucosa throughout the oesophagus (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely to have caused these endoscopic findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pregabalin","Omeprazole","Ranitidine","Ramipril","Tetracycline"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe endoscopic findings show white plaques characteristic of oesophageal candidiasis. This condition typically presents with odynophagia (pain on swallowing) and is most commonly seen following antibiotic use. \u003Cstrong\u003ETetracycline\u003C/strong\u003E and other broad-spectrum antibiotics disrupt the normal microbiome, allowing opportunistic overgrowth of \u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E. Prolonged antibiotic use, as in this case for acne treatment, particularly increases this risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E and other proton pump inhibitors can increase the risk of oesophageal candidiasis by reducing gastric acid production. However, this patient has been on acid suppression for many years without previous episodes, making this a less likely cause than the recent antibiotic use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERanitidine\u003C/strong\u003E, as an H2-receptor antagonist, also reduces acid production but is a much less common cause of candidiasis than either antibiotics or proton pump inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregabalin\u003C/strong\u003E is used for neuropathic pain and has no direct effect on oesophageal mucosa or fungal colonisation. Its main side effects include dizziness, drowsiness, and peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamipril\u003C/strong\u003E and other angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors can cause a dry cough but do not predispose to oesophageal candidiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of oesophageal candidiasis typically involves oral antifungal medications such as fluconazole, with resolution of symptoms usually occurring within a few days of starting treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oesophageal candidiasis commonly presents with odynophagia (pain on swallowing) and is characterised by white plaques on endoscopy","Recent antibiotic use is the most common risk factor for oesophageal candidiasis","Proton pump inhibitors and H2 antagonists are lesser risk factors for oesophageal candidiasis"],"references":["Holt JM. Candida infection of the oesophagus. Gut. 1968 Apr;9(2):227."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67658"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1605"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16852"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16852"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f31b5706-d093-42d2-9874-79352c84ca15.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f31b5706-d093-42d2-9874-79352c84ca15.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":570,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67658"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T19:27:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T19:29:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1605"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82495"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}